description: Policy Director at The League of American Bicyclists (@bikeleague). Most tweets are bike-related, but not always org-related.
tweets: Interesting psychology note, the 1959 report included a study of two cities 45 miles apart in the same state. The city that associated "speed" with slowing down and being careful had a better traffic safety record https://t.co/9vuBVzlgmH

name: Ken McLeod 🚴🚵🏃🚲
description: Policy Director at The League of American Bicyclists (@bikeleague). Most tweets are bike-related, but not always org-related.
tweets:
Only four states have urban or business district statutory speed limits of 20 mph - Alaska, Iowa, Nebraska, and Oregon

It is unclear how many miles of roadway are subject to those limits and I suspect most qualifying streets have speed limits set by ordinance or traffic study

name: Ken McLeod 🚴🚵🏃🚲
description: Policy Director at The League of American Bicyclists (@bikeleague). Most tweets are bike-related, but not always org-related.
tweets:
The 1956 change to recommend urban speed limits of 30 mph remained in effect until the last Uniform Vehicle Code in 2000

Now, the @WHO recommends speed limits of 30 kmh/20 mph in urban areas, and the US has no clear state coordinating mechanism to accomplish that change

name: Ken McLeod 🚴🚵🏃🚲
description: Policy Director at The League of American Bicyclists (@bikeleague). Most tweets are bike-related, but not always org-related.
tweets:
The 1956 timing was of interest to me because in 1956 the Uniform Vehicle Code raised its recommended urban speed limits from 25 mph to 30 mph.

Unfortunately, there's no mention of that policy change in the 1959 report and it doesn't appear that urban speeds were on their radar

name: Ken McLeod 🚴🚵🏃🚲
description: Policy Director at The League of American Bicyclists (@bikeleague). Most tweets are bike-related, but not always org-related.
tweets:
The only mention of people biking or walking in this 1959 report is about police being more effective at patrol on bikes vs. on foot
